1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:12,000
We were able to see so, I don't know.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
So what I'm going to do is a quick real marker for the...

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:19,000
No problem.

5
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:24,000
...and then what I like to do, I usually start to go fairly chronologically.

6
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:28,000
I always start with people's family histories and infectious words that came from me.

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:31,000
So, you've got some.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:33,000
So we'll start there and...

9
00:00:33,000 --> 00:00:38,000
Yeah, face to grandmother and grandfather who didn't play.

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,000
Oh and I should...

11
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:44,000
I'll also just tell you right now that because we were recording digitally,

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:47,000
we stop every once in a while to just save the files.

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:48,000
No problem.

14
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:49,000
We'll take a little break.

15
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:50,000
Yeah.

16
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:52,000
And anytime that you want to take a break, just let us know.

17
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Yeah, I've done.

18
00:00:53,000 --> 00:00:54,000
Yeah, okay.

19
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:58,000
And anywhere you want to take the interview, you take it.

20
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:04,000
You ever get to Ben Rouge, the new museum, state museums that's there, you hear me.

21
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:05,000
Okay.

22
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
And we did a lot of digital recording then.

23
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
So yeah, I've been on both sides though.

24
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:12,000
I've done a bunch of radio and stuff like that.

25
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,000
I like it on the side.

26
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Yeah.

27
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,000
All right, great.

28
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,000
I prefer that side, but yeah.

29
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:28,000
So today it is the tenth of May and we are at the African American Museum in Fair Park in Dallas, Texas.

30
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:31,000
This is David Cline talking.

31
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:37,000
David Cline from UNC Southern Oral History Project and Virginia Tech.

32
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,000
And I'm here with Charles Chuck Siler.

33
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:48,000
Also with John Bishop who is behind the camera, John Bishop of Media Generation and UCLA.

34
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:58,000
And we're all here today as part of the Civil Rights History Project on behalf of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's Museum of African American History and Culture.

35
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:02,000
And Chuck, I just wanted to say thank you so much for your part of this project.

36
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:03,000
You're welcome.

37
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:05,000
I'm happy to be here.

38
00:02:05,000 --> 00:02:12,000
And if we could start, if you could just tell us a little bit about the family into which you were born.

39
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And how you may have seen that environment shaping the kind of work and things that you went on to do.

40
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:27,000
Well, I think what is, I don't have to, I had a big family for one.

41
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:35,000
My mother and father were divorced early though my father and I did get to be good friends later in life.

42
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,000
My mother was a beautician.

43
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:41,000
And so naturally she was in a position to hear everybody's business.

44
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And I think she was well trusted because she didn't tell her what she heard.

45
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:50,000
My grandmother was a piano player.

46
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Her career was spent playing for churches, teaching music, choirs, this and that.

47
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:01,000
And I was her oldest grand, her first grandchild.

48
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
So I could have been a little bit spoiled.

49
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:11,000
My grandfather, I was the first grandchild that he had, that he had a chance to spend any time with.

50
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:14,000
And he was alive till I was seven.

51
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:20,000
So he was an influence in terms of the fact that he abetted my creativity.

52
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:26,000
I guess my grandmother found me when I was, as she said, about 50, 60 months old.

53
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:27,000
I found a pencil.

54
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:33,000
And we had these lower half of the walls in the house that they had bought were wooden.

55
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:37,000
And she saw me trying to draw on the wall.

56
00:03:37,000 --> 00:03:45,000
And her story was that I wasn't just scratching on the wall but I was trying to draw little stick figures and things.

57
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:51,000
So she gave me, told me if I wanted to do that, ask for paper and pencil.

58
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:58,000
And so two of the first words that I learned according to her were paper and pencil because she said I started asking her for that almost every day.

59
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:06,000
But the upside for her was she could put me in a corner with a pen, a big cheap Indian pad, which I remember.

60
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,000
And a pencil and leave me there all day.

61
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
So the upside was she used to always start out reading every day with the cartoons.

62
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:20,000
So the attitude was she'd get a laugh and first they'd get to the serious news.

63
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:27,000
And I come from a family of folk who had, I think, great senses of humor.

64
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:36,000
My father, in fact, also, when I got to know him as an adult, I discovered that his sense of humor was very well intact to him.

65
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And my mother is 92 and she still can be funny when she was too.

66
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:51,000
But my mother had six brothers, all of whom had a lot of influence on me.

67
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:57,000
And one of my father's, his oldest brother, Eugene, was another influence.

68
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:05,000
He lived about 40, 50 miles away and laughed for yet, but we were in contact.

69
00:05:05,000 --> 00:05:12,000
My family in Baton Rouge was one that encouraged me.

70
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:17,000
All of them were readers. So I grew up reading.

71
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:22,000
I started reading when I was, and my younger brother, when we were both about two.

72
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:25,000
You know, we were able to read a sentence and do things.

73
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
When I started school, I was five.

74
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:35,000
And they let me, you know, my first grade teacher was a neighbor.

75
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:39,000
And she took me because I was the only black kid in the neighborhood at the time.

76
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
And so I went to school with her.

77
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:48,000
And I did well enough that she asked the principal who also lived in the neighborhood.

78
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:58,000
But things were different then because my parents, my mother, had gone to school or had been taught by half of the same folk who taught me years later.

79
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,000
Everyone knew everyone else.

80
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:10,000
You know, I had relatives who, yeah, I had folk who, one of my aunts was secretary at my high school.

81
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:14,000
Another one taught, taught, taught home economics.

82
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:16,000
It was married to my mother's brother.

83
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:27,000
And so, you know, there were, those people there, my uncle Ralph was head custodian at my high school and became later parish white.

84
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:31,000
Supervisive custodial things in Baton Rouge.

85
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:36,000
So the family was very well known in terms of that.

86
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:39,000
He was also a caterer, great cook, you know.

87
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,000
And I learned a lot from that.

88
00:06:42,000 --> 00:06:46,000
My wife tells me she married me because I could read and cook.

89
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And I have to blame my family for that.

90
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:59,000
But at times too, when I did things that were sort of, as they like to say now out the box, I was supported by that.

91
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:09,000
You guys made me start thinking about this because I was trying to go back to when I first protested something.

92
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:16,000
And my first protest, as much as I laugh about it, now was against Boy Scouts.

93
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:23,000
Because in the 50s, when I was probably 11, 12 years old, we marched in the Boy Scout parade.

94
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:28,000
And we were proud of the fact that we had little drill teams and we could very moves and this and that.

95
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:35,000
But in Baton Rouge, they put the black boy Scouts behind the horses.

96
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:41,000
And I think I did it the first two years and I had to clean my shoes after that.

97
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:44,000
I decided I wasn't going to do that.

98
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:47,000
I had a scout master who wasn't in line with that with me.

99
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:52,000
So I quit the Boy Scouts and started an explorer post at my school.

100
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:58,000
But it was the first active protest that I did and got away with.

101
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:02,000
I went to McKinley High School in Baton Rouge.

102
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:13,000
McKinley was well known for being greater academics, greater athletics, and we would fight anybody and usually win.

103
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:21,000
And South Baton Rouge was, you know, in the city of Irwin, it wasn't as bad as some of the inner cities.

104
00:08:21,000 --> 00:08:24,000
Now we didn't shoot as many people.

105
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
Folk weren't getting a shot, this and that.

106
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,000
But you would fight and you had to learn to do that kind of thing.

107
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:37,000
When the Southern University demonstration in March of 1960 happened, they had to lock us on campus.

108
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:41,000
Because we were ready to go out and do it.

109
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:46,000
We started a little bit more about that when you said you were ready to go out.

110
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
In what way and what had you been?

111
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:49,000
We were ready to go and join the demonstration.

112
00:08:49,000 --> 00:08:51,000
You know, we heard about it.

113
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:54,000
Somebody said students from Southern are marching downtown.

114
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:00,000
And most of us were ready to say, let's go and join them.

115
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:04,000
You said you had a sense of what was going on for the Korean and the world community.

116
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:10,000
We knew because we had, you know, I've told kids this and I hate to say,

117
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:18,000
but I think the kids that I used to talk to about the Civil Rights Movement when I worked at the State Museum,

118
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:28,000
you may have that in Louisiana, but there were a few schools that I went to where they were interested in things like the Civil Rights Movement.

119
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:36,000
And there were social studies teachers who had the sides up, the white and black, you know, white and colored at that side.

120
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:39,000
And I told them about things that we used to do to protest.

121
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:48,000
You know, we would take a paper cup, go into the men's room, use it, and pour it over the white water fountain.

122
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:55,000
It was our way of protesting what we could, you know, because we couldn't, you know, and we were treated bad.

123
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,000
You know, folk would throw money at you.

124
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:04,000
My uncle Jean started the first black cleaners in Lafayette, Louisiana.

125
00:10:04,000 --> 00:10:11,000
He had to, when he, in the early days, sit in his shop at night with his gun.

126
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:17,000
Because they threw bricks, they shot, they said, but he had a reputation for shooting back.

127
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:23,000
And he was, he was a person that, until he died, I love the man.

128
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:28,000
Like, he was, you know, he felt that since my father and mother had divorced and they gone,

129
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:34,000
he felt obligated to be close to me, keep me linked to the silo side of the family well.

130
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:42,000
The silo's had left Alabama, my uncles and my father and that much because they had a reputation for shooting back.

131
00:10:42,000 --> 00:10:49,000
And, and mobile, in that area where they were from, in the 30s and 40s, that wasn't a part of it.

132
00:10:49,000 --> 00:10:54,000
My father also played baseball, which let him see a lot of it.

133
00:10:54,000 --> 00:11:04,000
He had some good friend, Satchel Paige was one of them that I happened to meet once and I thought that was one of the great moments of my life in 1967.

134
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:09,000
But my father stayed involved with baseball most of his life.

135
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:13,000
He started the Compton County Mac baseball league.

136
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:19,000
And he had, he told me the stories about the fights that they had in California.

137
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:23,000
But that league sent over 600 players to the pros.

138
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And when I worked at Southern for a few years later, I started with one of the coaches at Southern League Flint Royate,

139
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:36,000
played ball with my father, put a black pelicans in New Orleans.

140
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:43,000
And when he found out that he played third base, second base and my father was a shortstop.

141
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,000
And he said, you're a child or son, dad, I tell you.

142
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:53,000
And I put them in touch and a lot of guys out of Compton went through Southern and to the other HBCUs.

143
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:58,000
So you know, little things like that, that family network of sorts.

144
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:05,000
Most of my uncles, with possibly one exception, worked for themselves.

145
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:12,000
My uncle Peter, who was one of those that I was named after. His name was Ernest, by hits the E.

146
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:18,000
In my name, my uncle T.J. was an insurance salesman.

147
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:26,000
Most of them had been in World War II. All of them, my uncle Earl was a tailor.

148
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:33,000
They had learned these things. My two younger uncles had been in Korea.

149
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:40,000
Well, one was in Korea, one was in service as a medic during the Korean War, but he couldn't get a job when he got out.

150
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:51,000
So he worked as a waiter, and like I said, he was the one who later became supervisor in the Baden's Urge School District of custodial services and things.

151
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:59,000
And he had his own business until, long after he retired. The thing was they tended to be independent.

152
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:08,000
My grandfather spoiled me. Like I said, I was the first grandchild that he had in two families to have time with.

153
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:19,000
And so, you know, we would listen to all the old radio shows when he had to babysit me because my grandmother had choir rehearsals and things during the week. This was her living.

154
00:13:19,000 --> 00:13:25,000
And she made, for that time, a fairly good living, playing music.

155
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:34,000
Our first thing, and John would appreciate this, that she told me was a story about what got her in the gospel.

156
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:43,000
One part was she was raised by her uncle and aunt, who, her uncle was a Methodist minister named Mansfield Jones.

157
00:13:43,000 --> 00:13:49,000
But she got punished because she was playing blues. She liked to play the blues.

158
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:57,000
She played a stride piano. There's a piano player out there now who I've heard play with her, and I wish I had recorded it.

159
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:03,000
And Henry Butler, who has a style very similar, big left hand, big clapping left hand.

160
00:14:03,000 --> 00:14:08,000
And she played the yellow dog blues for me. I have loved the blues ever since.

161
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,000
Okay, for all she did with gospel, the blues got me, okay.

162
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:18,000
And a lot of my friends that I grew up with had batted, and we were just blues players and things like that.

163
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:22,000
And so we, you know, are still, I'm still tied to that.

164
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:35,000
The act of civil disobedience, my senior year in high school after the Southern demonstration, a group of us,

165
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:47,000
I'm trying to remember names, Moses Edwards, Betty Jones, E. Nola Price, the oldest Washington who's not with us any longer,

166
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:53,000
were among, we were a part of the end, some of us were in double ACPU Council, folks.

167
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:58,000
Betty Jones. Betty G. Jones, yeah.

168
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:13,000
And I think Moses is still alive. We graduated in class of 60, but after we took our final examinations about two weeks before we were supposed to march,

169
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:23,000
we decided that we were going to pull our protests. And so my family looked up one night and there was with a picket sign in front of the state library,

170
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:29,000
because we had tried to use it. And they didn't let us in.

171
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:35,000
So we, there was a, was there black, there was a black, so called black branch somewhere.

172
00:15:35,000 --> 00:15:49,000
There were black, black, black, we had to call the branch library. And I spent a lot of time there because they finally, at one point, moved around the corner from my house.

173
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:59,000
I would, you know, they had to read 12 books and you get the certificate thing. Then I'd read 40 books in the summertime so I could have three or four centimeters, you know.

174
00:15:59,000 --> 00:16:09,000
But Miss Bennett, who was the librarian, had a son, Herbert Bennett, who was one of my first teachers, who was a very talented artist.

175
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:22,000
As I said at that time, I had an uncle, Willie Jr., we called him son, who was also a very talented artist. But at that time there was very little outlet there.

176
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:30,000
And my uncle's son had to leave Baton Rouge because he had gotten into a fight with some guys.

177
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:42,000
The best description I can give you of him is he was, he looked like Burt Lancaster in brown face. He was about six feet tall.

178
00:16:42,000 --> 00:16:51,000
And he had a Charles Atlas build, but he had been driving trucks and loading trucks since he was 10, 11 years old for the Bologna brothers at Baton Rouge.

179
00:16:51,000 --> 00:16:58,000
And so he had this bill that was there. He died after being shot by another American soldier.

180
00:16:59,000 --> 00:17:04,000
Well, he didn't die immediately. He lived nine more years, but he was shot with a machine gun.

181
00:17:04,000 --> 00:17:13,000
And he had probably almost 60 surgeries over the years, removing shrapnel as it came to the surface.

182
00:17:13,000 --> 00:17:21,000
But during that time, he was very much an influence on me also because he was encouraging when it came to my art.

183
00:17:21,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And he showed me that he could draw.

184
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:31,000
And I had never seen anybody do it that well, nobody black.

185
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:38,000
I'd seen all of these other things. And later when I had a chance to study with some, I think, great artist.

186
00:17:38,000 --> 00:17:43,000
I was able to appreciate it because some of them had come there.

187
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:58,000
My uncles and my grandmother, particularly when we hit the state library, I'm going back to that, didn't put me out of the house.

188
00:17:58,000 --> 00:18:00,000
You know, they.

189
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:01,000
Can I stop you just for a second?

190
00:18:01,000 --> 00:18:02,000
Yeah.

191
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:07,000
One is you mentioned sort of you are on the customer graduation.

192
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:09,000
So there was a thing issue going on.

193
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:15,000
So if you could say a little bit about that. And then also specifically what it was that why you targeted the library.

194
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:17,000
We couldn't use it.

195
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:24,000
And I was like I said, I at Carver branch, I tried these.

196
00:18:24,000 --> 00:18:31,000
I don't know if I read every book in the library, but I read most of what I could find out.

197
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:37,000
Okay. And one, I went through one phase where I lived.

198
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:42,000
The part of Baton Rouge where I grew up in one point in this history, it's called Markets and Old.

199
00:18:42,000 --> 00:18:51,000
We had snakes all over the place. Every kind of snake, you know, I mean my backyard was a veritable.

200
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,000
We.

201
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:56,000
To overcome fear.

202
00:18:56,000 --> 00:19:00,000
I went and read everything I could all snakes.

203
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:05,000
And one point I wanted to be a herpetologist, I drew snakes, sketch snakes.

204
00:19:05,000 --> 00:19:11,000
And I had teachers again like Ben Hall who was my biology teacher.

205
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:16,000
Mr. Hall let me bring a pet snake in for demonstration.

206
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:19,000
It was a hognose snake.

207
00:19:19,000 --> 00:19:21,000
Let me doctor a country.

208
00:19:21,000 --> 00:19:27,000
His name was Irving. He became a cartoon later too.

209
00:19:27,000 --> 00:19:33,000
But Irving was the first opportunity that I had to do this.

210
00:19:33,000 --> 00:19:42,000
I had teachers who always taught us, saying when I was in school was that you had to be twice as good if you were black to get half as much.

211
00:19:42,000 --> 00:19:47,000
My teacher said, okay, you got to be three, four, five times as good.

212
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:50,000
And we grew up with that.

213
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:59,000
We had silent support from a lot of them even though they couldn't speak up when we went out and protested.

214
00:19:59,000 --> 00:20:06,000
Now the reason we did it for the most part after we we had been planning it.

215
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:16,000
But the reason we waited until after we finished our examinations was because of the fact that they couldn't use missing that against us.

216
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:19,000
Okay, and we had about two weeks.

217
00:20:19,000 --> 00:20:31,000
We finished examinations and about this time in May, I graduated once the 26th, which I'll never forget because it was my aunt's birthday and later my wedding day.

218
00:20:31,000 --> 00:20:34,000
We were married on the 26th of May.

219
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:41,000
But during that time we started our protest.

220
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:44,000
We started picoting, we started doing things.

221
00:20:44,000 --> 00:20:46,000
And they had to watch us.

222
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:58,000
And there were other kids at Southern High, a few from Capitol, who were Capitol Avenue, another one of the schools, who were getting involved in the activity because greenville had happened.

223
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:00,000
Then Southern happened.

224
00:21:00,000 --> 00:21:09,000
People don't know this, but Southern's first demonstration was the largest of the mass demonstrations to hit the South in 1960.

225
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:18,000
Marvin Robinson + Marvin Robinson + Donald Moss + Major Johns + Major Johns, who lives here in Dallas now, he's recovering from a stroke I was told.

226
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:22,000
Marvin Robinson + Donald Moss + Major Johns, who I think is back in Louisiana, I'm not certain.

227
00:21:22,000 --> 00:21:26,000
But I've got a friend in Baton Rouge, Mayo, Bruce, who was from Marvin Robinson + Donald Moss + Major Johns.

228
00:21:26,000 --> 00:21:32,000
In Marvin Robinson + Donald Moss + Major Johns, they tried to integrate the library there and he had a good put to his here about a sheriff.

229
00:21:33,000 --> 00:21:40,000
And when he tells that story about it, I've never seen him talk about it without becoming emotional.

230
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:48,000
But if you've ever been shot at him or if you've ever had someone threaten you that way, you don't forget that.

231
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:57,000
And it was something that made me, it made it difficult for me to be nonviolent later.

232
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
I met Martin Luther King in 1962.

233
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:15,000
I had a chance to shake his hand and he at the NAACP convention in Atlanta walked around, came around the room and shook every by all the young folks, shook our hands.

234
00:22:15,000 --> 00:22:23,000
And gave us a word or two of encouragement, but I'll have to backtrack to get to that point.

235
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:29,000
But they wanted to put us out of school in 60, but they couldn't.

236
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:40,000
One reason being all of the guys that I named that were a part of this that I can remember now were the best students in the class.

237
00:22:40,000 --> 00:22:50,000
Our valedictorian and salutatorian didn't participate, but then again, different reasons.

238
00:22:50,000 --> 00:22:59,000
Most of us were the ones who had gone through it, who lived out there with it, who put up with it, and we weren't as sheltered.

239
00:22:59,000 --> 00:23:04,000
And we were very forward and we were going to be out there saying what we had to say.

240
00:23:04,000 --> 00:23:09,000
So we did what we could, we started that.

241
00:23:09,000 --> 00:23:16,000
Things settled down a bit and all of us went wherever to school. I went to Southern.

242
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:25,000
You talked a little bit about this already, but the support behind you, I mentioned this again.

243
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:28,000
So clearly you've got some of you have your families.

244
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:38,000
You talked about, I mean, your family so many because of this history of independent business owners and this kind of independence that your family actually had.

245
00:23:38,000 --> 00:23:42,000
But you often see in competitions.

246
00:23:42,000 --> 00:23:55,000
One of the things that was funny, my uncle Ralph, when my grandmother died and I was talking after the funeral and he told me, he says, you know your grandfather used to write my grandfather wrote a bicycle to work.

247
00:23:55,000 --> 00:24:01,000
He had worked on the railroad and as he got two old to work trains, he became the janitor at the roundhouse in Baton Rouge.

248
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:05,000
I remember going with him when I was about three, four years old.

249
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:08,000
He suddenly took me down to Cedar and he's giant trains.

250
00:24:08,000 --> 00:24:19,000
You know, when you, that tall in the train is 20 feet, it looks huge and everybody knew Willie, you know, as he was.

251
00:24:19,000 --> 00:24:22,000
And he always wrote a bicycle to work.

252
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:27,000
And my uncle Ralph told me, he says, you know, daddy wrote a bike and that's what we all called him daddy.

253
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:34,000
He says to work because he wasn't going to pay a dime and have somebody to tell him where to sit on the bus.

254
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:38,000
Okay, he generally wrote, or cover alls to work.

255
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:48,000
But every Sunday morning he was had Deacon at his church, he was in a suit and he would walk to church, you know, so I've gone with him a few times here there.

256
00:24:48,000 --> 00:24:59,000
But he was, you know, he was, he was a model for manhood and I was his oldest grandchild.

257
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:04,000
And at that time he was going to, you know, give it.

258
00:25:04,000 --> 00:25:13,000
I didn't know that then but whatever was there was a part of what later made me understand that I could speak up.

259
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:23,000
And I had learned from my mother and from my grandmother that right or wrong, if I felt I was right, I was going to say it.

260
00:25:23,000 --> 00:25:40,000
Now sometimes I got spanked for it, but my mother learned early on that I was hard-headed enough that if I knew I was right and she learned that she could speak me and I told her the last time I got a spanking I said, well, you can do this, but I'm not going to cry.

261
00:25:40,000 --> 00:25:46,000
And so I took the spanking and I looked back at it and my question was, are you finished?

262
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:58,000
I never got another one, but I had to sacrifice that because then I had my mother and my grandmother in each year in stereo talking to me about what I had done wrong, what I did.

263
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,000
So I was kept on track.

264
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:06,000
In school, I had some teachers.

265
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:10,000
Mr. Hall was one in particular.

266
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:15,000
I ran into his grandson a few weeks ago here that I hadn't known.

267
00:26:15,000 --> 00:26:24,000
Mr. Altamous, who had been in World War II also with my uncles and things, who had what we now call post-traumatic stress disorder.

268
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:33,000
I didn't understand, you know, guys would laugh because they said they could set off a firecrack at Mr. Altamus with diamonds or the death columns.

269
00:26:33,000 --> 00:26:46,000
Well, when I got back from Vietnam, I apologized to Mr. Altamous for having been one of those guys who would laugh when somebody did something like that and say, oh, Mr. Altamous-." well, I understood why he drove onto the desk.

270
00:26:46,000 --> 00:26:49,000
I had been through rocket attacks and things like that.

271
00:26:49,000 --> 00:26:58,000
Okay, so those loud noises, I still got to know us from being too close to a howitzer, you know, without protection.

272
00:26:58,000 --> 00:27:06,000
And those kind of things, you know, you learn to appreciate later in life.

273
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:13,000
But these were the guys who also were supporting us quietly.

274
00:27:13,000 --> 00:27:17,000
They didn't want to lose their jobs. We didn't want them to lose their jobs.

275
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:23,000
But they didn't say, I never heard you wrong.

276
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:29,000
You know, Mr. Hall has two, some daughters who are still alive who are like little sisters of mine.

277
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:39,000
Because Mr. Hall would sit there and tell you what they, you know, and we heard the stories of what people had gone through and they were reinforced.

278
00:27:39,000 --> 00:27:53,000
And in the neighborhood, all of that, Dr. Dr. Dupuy H. Anderson, whose father was a member of the end of, was on the board of the NAACP in Baton Rouge,

279
00:27:53,000 --> 00:27:59,000
we were on a panel together at LSU in February of this year.

280
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:09,000
And Dr. Dr. Dupuy H. Anderson, who was a dentist, was one of the leaders of the Civil Right Movement in Baton Rouge.

281
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:16,000
In 1961, I started off, I was a foot soldier, I wasn't one of the leaders.

282
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:20,000
I got involved because they needed somebody to make science.

283
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:30,000
I was an art major. And Diana Manning, who died a few years ago, and I were two of the first art majors to make science.

284
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:41,000
Yeah, protest science. We were at Southern. I was a sophomore. The funny thing is, I was a person, I was a member of the person rifle,

285
00:28:41,000 --> 00:28:51,000
and I was a real team, and I was at the time of Pledgey, and I later became a PR, but five team leaders next to me was Hubert Gerold "H. Rap" Brown.

286
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:59,000
Hubert Gerold "H. Rap" Brown, who later became known as Hubert Gerold "H. Rap" Brown. I've known him since junior high school.

287
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:05,000
We got to be close in college because we used to hitchhike to school together. We lived in the same part of town.

288
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:15,000
For protection in part two, because it wasn't easy to be out there, and it was always easier to hitchhike with somebody.

289
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:20,000
We would do that from Southern because we didn't have bus service to the school.

290
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:24,000
If you were up there late at night, we had to get home, so it was either walk.

291
00:29:24,000 --> 00:29:29,000
There was a part of Baton Rouge called Dixie that we didn't really want to walk through at night.

292
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:39,000
Because anything could happen on scenic highway. We tried to catch people coming off campus going on, and everybody got to know us over a period of time.

293
00:29:39,000 --> 00:29:51,000
In 1961, we started doing this, and then they started teaching us nonviolent protests, you know, how to go into the famous curl in the whole thing if you were getting beaten.

294
00:29:51,000 --> 00:30:07,000
We had sessions at the college and off campus. We got to let us use his place, and after he closed it moved the tables aside.

295
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:17,000
We had Dave Dennis Sr from Corps Jerome Smith, who was still a new audience. He runs in a organization called Tambourine & Fan.

296
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:29,000
We were all fault Jerome Smith. Jerome was a freedom writer.

297
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:36,000
He has stories that, like I said, he was a leader. Ronnie Moore is still a new audience.

298
00:30:36,000 --> 00:30:50,000
Rani's daughter, Desi, is married to Wess Anderson. Rani, I think, is still running a program or working at Tulane if I'm correct.

299
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:54,000
We're actually going to talk to D'Army Bailey.

300
00:30:54,000 --> 00:30:56,000
Yeah, I know Darmi.

301
00:30:56,000 --> 00:30:58,000
Can I underline for a second?

302
00:30:58,000 --> 00:31:00,000
Yeah.

303
00:31:00,000 --> 00:31:10,000
I'm saying two things that you... One is... Could you tell us what happened with the man who got to the shooting gun by a white malnose third story about that?

304
00:31:10,000 --> 00:31:16,000
My uncle? My uncle just happened to be a person that would fight back.

305
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:22,000
The reason he had to leave Baton Rouge was because he got two guys jumped him.

306
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:28,000
It was during a time when they could get away with things like beating up on Black Folk.

307
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:38,000
I knew of cases where cops would have Billy Club practice as some folk we used to call it on people.

308
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:50,000
My uncle, as I said, was one of... He was strong enough to take the front of a Volkswagen. He could literally lift it on a system.

309
00:31:50,000 --> 00:31:54,000
He hit a guy and supposedly broke his neck from what I was doing.

310
00:31:54,000 --> 00:32:06,000
And he had to leave. When he got drafted, he was working in a war plan, a munitions plan, a something of North and Kansas or somewhere like that as close as I can get to it.

311
00:32:06,000 --> 00:32:18,000
And he had changed his name. He added an R instead of Willie Moton Jr. The family name was Moton in Louisiana.

312
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:26,000
He added an R. He was Willie Morton Jr. That was enough in those days to get out of that.

313
00:32:26,000 --> 00:32:32,000
But he went into the military. I don't know what prompted it.

314
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:38,000
But he was a person who would fight back.

315
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:44,000
And generally, he was a person whom if you had a fight with, he was going to...

316
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:52,000
I didn't want him to ever hit me. He made me go back and fight a guy who was bigger than me once.

317
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:59,000
And I stayed in the fight more out of fear of him than getting hurt.

318
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And I took a good butt weapon for about half an hour before the other guy gave up.

319
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:10,000
Because every time I wanted to stop, I looked and he'd be standing there just watching me.

320
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:17,000
And after it was all over, he told me, he says, I didn't say you had to win the fight. He said it said you had to fight.

321
00:33:17,000 --> 00:33:23,000
And once he says, bullies don't want people to fight back.

322
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:32,000
Oh, he says they were. I never had another fight with that guy here because he understood that I was going to...

323
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:40,000
My uncle died not long after that. But one of those pieces of shrapnel knicked something and you know, that killed him.

324
00:33:40,000 --> 00:33:48,000
And he was like 39 years old at the time. But the thing was, you know, it was one of the lessons I learned.

325
00:33:48,000 --> 00:33:59,000
My uncle, Gene, who my wife knew and my son also got to know, after his experience in Lafayette,

326
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:07,000
moved out of the heart of town into a little area called Scott that at the time was fairly well unincorporated.

327
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:20,000
But he had about two acres of land, maybe three. And he was never further away than maybe 20 feet from one of his hidden guns.

328
00:34:20,000 --> 00:34:24,000
Because he was always wary of that.

329
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:30,000
My father was also, you know, all of them. They weren't in R.A.

330
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:35,000
But the terrorists, they were worried about were a totally different brand.

331
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:42,000
One of the brothers, Earl, became a minister in Perris, California.

332
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:49,000
And his son, Don, is a bishop now. I don't know how to do these things. I'm not a good church girl, OK?

333
00:34:49,000 --> 00:34:53,000
But the family has a history like that.

334
00:34:53,000 --> 00:35:00,000
My uncle, Gene used to tell me, he says, I didn't shoot the sheriff, he says, but I almost shot the deputy.

335
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:08,000
And they were looking for him at one point. And the guy who was the deputy that saw where he was hiding was a friend of his.

336
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:14,000
And knew he wasn't guilty of anything. And told the guy he wasn't there.

337
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:21,000
This is the story he told me later. He said, and so he was able to get away and get away from mobile.

338
00:35:21,000 --> 00:35:27,000
And he said, no, he had to leave. And so, you know, I had that growing up.

339
00:35:27,000 --> 00:35:32,000
I had these guys, these voices in my, and all of them were standing up.

340
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:36,000
My uncle Ralph, the funniest story that I've ever heard.

341
00:35:36,000 --> 00:35:47,000
He was a guy walked up to him when he was on his knees, saying his prayers in the barracks when he was in the army and started playing the dozens with him.

342
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:54,000
And when my uncle Ralph got up, beat the guy.

343
00:35:54,000 --> 00:36:01,000
I mean, beat him really good, then turned around, got back on his knees and finished saying his prayers.

344
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:13,000
You know, and I always had these guys saying, you know, so when it came down to that, when I was 19 years old and that activity started,

345
00:36:13,000 --> 00:36:22,000
I was going to be a part of it. And I went from painting protest signs to going through the training.

346
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:30,000
And then I went on a city in the first time. And that was, you know, different because I joke about it.

347
00:36:30,000 --> 00:36:38,000
Now, I can't help it. I think it's a part of what made me decide that maybe at 80, I'm going to become a full time stand-up comic or something.

348
00:36:38,000 --> 00:36:47,000
Every guy that the terrorists that we had to deal with, I don't know where they got these guys from.

349
00:36:47,000 --> 00:36:57,000
But there were, you guys all 6, 8, 6, 9, they looked like pro football players. They didn't have their hoods on, but you know, we knew who they were.

350
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:03,000
And they were there to intimidate. Well, at the time, I might have weighed 175, 180 pounds.

351
00:37:04,000 --> 00:37:11,000
I was the same height that I am now, but that's a lot of difference when it comes to looking at 300 pounds.

352
00:37:11,000 --> 00:37:27,000
And there were arms as big as my waistline was at the time. So, I became more of an observer to a point after that because my attitude was going to be that if something happened, I was going to have to fight.

353
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:42,000
You know, if no more than just to get away, but I, you know, was not good at seeing women get hit or thinking I could take that without, you know, some kind of response to it.

354
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:59,000
We went to jail, 12th of December, if I recall the day correctly, a group of us were arrested and taken downtown to, for picketing, we were picketing the Bon Marché Center, I think. I don't throw it a street.

355
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:12,000
And we were taken into the bad room's jail and we were given the usual, if you come back down here, we're putting you in jail, we're going to keep you up to our, you know.

356
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:25,000
And Willie Bradford, who's in Shreveport now, Willie Bradford, Thomas Pete, Jane, Theta Ambrose, I think was with us.

357
00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:37,000
I'm trying to remember Janelle's last name and it just slipped my mind, but Bradford turned their cop and said, what are you going to do with the other 5,000?

358
00:38:37,000 --> 00:38:51,000
And this guy turned red. I thought he was ready to hit him, but Bradford and the thing I think it made it even worse was Brad was black, but Brad was, if you didn't know, he was black you.

359
00:38:52,000 --> 00:39:07,000
You know, couldn't, but he was, you know, he knew and he wasn't hiding it. And he and Thomas Peete, who are very light skinned guys, I think sometimes enraged the race is more so than the darker folk did.

360
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:15,000
You know, they knew why we, but these guys didn't necessarily, you know, they could have slipped across the line and passed not.

361
00:39:15,000 --> 00:39:23,000
And Southern always looked like an integrated school because of the different, the broad range of color that you had there.

362
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:36,000
And so the next day we went back out, we protested again and we were on a bond to jail. I spent the Christmas holidays of 1961 and the East Baton Rouge Parish jail.

363
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:53,000
Now the day after that, not just Southern University students, but Baton Rouge citizens joined the march and they had from what I was told from the guys who were down there, at least 5,000 people were down there.

364
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:56,000
The press underplated.

365
00:39:56,000 --> 00:40:06,000
But we were up on the line on top of the jail house and it was split. There was a neutral area and there were cells on one side, cells on the street side.

366
00:40:06,000 --> 00:40:13,000
And we were, we walked over to the street side and we were standing up looking out at the windows and we could see the crowd assemble.

367
00:40:13,000 --> 00:40:20,000
And there were people going in both directions as far as we could see through the oak trees that were down there.

368
00:40:20,000 --> 00:40:25,000
And they were protesting, they were protesting our arrest.

369
00:40:25,000 --> 00:40:36,000
Yeah. We had been arrested once. There was a rally tonight when we got back. We went back out the next day because they dared us to come back and we took the dare.

370
00:40:36,000 --> 00:40:44,000
Okay. Or I don't, if I recall correctly, I didn't stay at home that night because they, so I was afraid somebody might try to talk me out of it.

371
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:56,000
But we went back downtown. One of the things I was kind of good at was whenever we had protest, I used to get to do, I had to stick with voices.

372
00:40:56,000 --> 00:41:12,000
And when I knew sometime, you know, I didn't tell the guys I was doing this all the time, but I would get on the phone and call down to the police and call in a report that they had some knee-resout there.

373
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:22,000
And that they were over here, they're all over the place. And they would go this way and we'd be over here.

374
00:41:22,000 --> 00:41:41,000
And, you know, I had that streak. I, you know, I still have it. I couldn't be different. But we went back down. They came and they put 340 of us plus in a space that was built for about 42 people.

375
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:54,000
When the demonstration came downtown, we were looking out and we saw, you know, everybody's dressed neatly. Nobody's about to start anything.

376
00:41:54,000 --> 00:42:02,000
And they started singing. We should overcome. And we started singing back.

377
00:42:02,000 --> 00:42:12,000
Okay, it was 13 of us then. And now or later they had, they were bringing them in, you know, from this.

378
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:13,000
But...

379
00:42:13,000 --> 00:42:15,000
It was a 13th in the first day.

380
00:42:15,000 --> 00:42:26,000
Yeah, we were in jail. On one side, the girls were, there was a wall separating us in the girls line, or the female line as, you know, the women's line.

381
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:43,000
And we started singing back. From a top to jail, yeah, they could hear us. And, you know, you got kind of a cheer or something that went up and they started singing and then all of a sudden we heard pop, pop, pop and dolls.

382
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:54,000
And the police actually rioted. It wasn't the protesters. They were peaceful. But just the song, we should overcome, set them off.

383
00:42:54,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And they used enough tear gas. And we were on like, what would have been the fourth, fifth floor of the building, I guess.

384
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:10,000
We could smell the tear gas in the line. They moved us and locked down that half of the jail.

385
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:21,000
So that we couldn't get into the cells on that side. They later opened it back up because we didn't have anywhere to go. It was almost standing room only.

386
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:29,000
Okay, we all came out of there a lot older than we went in. We were in there for three weeks.

387
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:49,000
When we came out, it was January 2nd, I guess. And our lawyers, Lolis Elie + (Bob) Collins + (Nils) Douglas, Lolis Elie, Robert F. Collins and Nils R. Douglas, came to get us out.

388
00:43:49,000 --> 00:44:01,000
Lolis Elie and I are still friends. His son is a journalist who is now living in L.A. He worked on the "Treme" television series as a story editor.

389
00:44:01,000 --> 00:44:10,000
But Lolis used to write for the pick of union in New Orleans. His father was a little guy. He was about five, four, five, five.

390
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:26,000
And when they brought us downstairs to release us, he came through a crowd of giant deputies. And it was like Moses parting the waters.

391
00:44:26,000 --> 00:44:45,000
And Lolis was fearless, I guess you say. That's the only thing I can think of that is cry there. He's another person whom, you know, if I had to recommend people to talk to, is in New Orleans, and I said, you got to talk to Lolis Elie.

392
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:58,000
Okay, because his stories were, had to be great. But we continued the protests when we got out of jail.

393
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:03,000
Felt in Clark, who was president of the University of Southern.

394
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:05,000
Did you get bailed out or how to do get bailed out?

395
00:45:05,000 --> 00:45:12,000
We were bailed out, yes. Which illegal picketing, things like that.

396
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:28,000
The charges were thrown out before we ever got to trial. But they had really, they knew it was most of the reason we were in jail was to quash the protest.

397
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:46,000
You know, jail was used as a punitive form of punishment. It wasn't about whether we were right or wrong. It was that we shouldn't, we were out of, you know, we were uppity.

398
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:54,000
Okay. And I've been called that since then. So it's not gone, you know, and I mean recently.

399
00:45:54,000 --> 00:45:58,000
It was like a few long, good luck.

400
00:45:58,000 --> 00:46:00,000
Oh, great.

401
00:46:00,000 --> 00:46:04,000
Okay. So I got to pick up a laptop.

402
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:18,000
Okay. When we were all finally, you know, banned from campus, again, somehow some of the people who were friendly.

403
00:46:18,000 --> 00:46:28,000
And since I lived in Baton Rouge, I was able to ease off to an awful campus to visit, you know, see my girlfriend at the time.

404
00:46:28,000 --> 00:46:35,000
Things like that. But I started work well and we were expelled as a kid.

405
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:41,000
Yeah. They there were a variety of different reasons, you know, grades, this and that.

406
00:46:41,000 --> 00:46:48,000
I was bored. I think my grades were probably borderline because of the fact that I'd missed so many classes and things like that.

407
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:56,000
Though I passed, I'm trying to remember if I flunked anything, I may have had flunked one course was up to because of that.

408
00:46:56,000 --> 00:47:05,000
But we were all put out of school, basically. And a lot of people didn't return to school as it was all to bad.

409
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:15,000
I was, like I said, 19 years old or 62. I made 1962. In fact, I was 18 still.

410
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:31,000
But Rev. T.J. Jemison, Reverend Robert Walker, who were within double-ACP and Baden Rouge offered me a job working for the NAACP running a voter registration project.

411
00:47:31,000 --> 00:47:44,000
And I walked over, I guess, two-thirds of the Southern part of Baton Rouge, door to door, trying to teach people how to pass what was supposed to be.

412
00:47:44,000 --> 00:47:50,000
And I say, in quotes of voter registration tests, basically it was a form that they had to fill out.

413
00:47:51,000 --> 00:48:03,000
And any and every excuse that could be used, you know, short of giving your birthday down to the second was used to keep people out.

414
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:10,000
We found some old voter registration forms and tests and things that they used to give that round ahead.

415
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:17,000
And she's had students nowadays who look at them and can't believe what they had to go through then.

416
00:48:17,000 --> 00:48:35,000
I worked out of an office on South 13th Street. And I always think back about that because it was an area where when I was a kid I had worked as a shoe-shy and boy and clean up guy at a barbershop on 13th and government street in Baton Rouge.

417
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:44,000
I was born about three blocks away on South 13th. It's now Eddie Robinson Sr. Drive after the coach from Brownlee.

418
00:48:44,000 --> 00:48:54,000
And you know, it's funny because Eddie and my mother and that were all classmates. And they all went to Leland College and stuff like that before.

419
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:03,000
But we, I worked that area. Fortunately in that area most of the black people knew me.

420
00:49:03,000 --> 00:49:10,000
So I had some who would determine not to get involved. One guy chased me out of his yard with a hole.

421
00:49:10,000 --> 00:49:19,000
Another one had a dog that wouldn't let me out of the yard once I got in. You know, he wanted to play. But whenever I started toward the gate he growled.

422
00:49:19,000 --> 00:49:26,000
So when the man got home he let me out. But I was active with the NAACP there.

423
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:30,000
Why was that you think that some words to reluctant to get involved with you?

424
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:42,000
Fear? You know, they didn't want to lose their jobs. I had a few relatives. Usually it wasn't the immediate relatives.

425
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:49,000
You know, those who may not have liked what I did didn't say anything because they would have to put up with my grandmother.

426
00:49:49,000 --> 00:50:01,000
And my grandmother backed me. I have to give her a credit for that. She knew that sometimes it had to happen.

427
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:14,000
And that I had been raised to stand up. And so it was consistent with how, with my upbringing I guess, if I had to say anything like that.

428
00:50:14,000 --> 00:50:26,000
And it was me, I guess. You know, I was also still trying to write and do things like that.

429
00:50:26,000 --> 00:50:35,000
And so through the spring and the summer of 1962 I worked out of that office during the protests.

430
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:50,000
The NAACP Secretary, Lady N. Pearl George, who was just a few years older than I was at the time, worked in the office with me when, you know, she wasn't going to school herself and doing whatever.

431
00:50:50,000 --> 00:51:04,000
She became a city council person years later. But Reverend Rev. T.J. Jemison, aren't the Rev. T.J. Jemison and Reverend Walker were the two, and Dr. Dr. Dupuy H. Anderson were the two.

432
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:22,000
The NA Folk, who were closest to me at the time, I, and I guess I'm, I can say this now, I got, I went to the NAACP convention in Atlanta in 1962 representing Baton Rouge.

433
00:51:22,000 --> 00:51:38,000
And I walked in and almost started to fly with a clansman outside the Atlanta convention center. They were picketing the, and, you know, I stopped in the middle of their picket line to make them walk, you know, in 19 years old.

434
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:50,000
I just turned 19 at the time. And so I was, you know, I was almost 200 pounds and big enough to think that I could be. And the guys had to say, come on, you know, I'm going to eat you wherever I'm off of this.

435
00:51:50,000 --> 00:51:59,000
But a guy named me out Jones and I during the middle of that convention pool of city and had a little place called a crystal in Atlanta.

436
00:51:59,000 --> 00:52:15,000
And we had some kids and Jewish kids who were there, went in, bought food, and had his sitting in front of us. We walked in, they got up and let us sit down and we proceeded to eating well.

437
00:52:15,000 --> 00:52:32,000
They didn't know what to do with us. So they locked the place, put hot water on the stove and pots, turned them up and steamed up the place. Basically, I guess trying to, you know, heat.

438
00:52:32,000 --> 00:52:53,000
Okay, I went to Vietnam because it wasn't cold. Okay, so heat wasn't going to run us out. And Al, I hope he's still alive. From say, look, yeah, you know, it's like I'm from Louisiana, you know, you know, summer or not. You know, you don't steam me out of a place. I think that's going to do it. I've been in much worse than that.

439
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:14,000
And we got in the sort of hot water with some of the NAACP leadership because we didn't know at the time that we weren't supposed to have done that because they had sort of had a no protest agreement going on.

440
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:22,000
And nobody told us about that because I was there alone.

441
00:53:22,000 --> 00:53:37,000
Ralph Cassimere, Dr. Raphael Cassimere, who was with the New Orleans chapter, was there then. We didn't know each other, but I ran for a national office during that time for the Youth Commission.

442
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:57,000
And they finally got rid of me on the fourth vote. Okay, but Clara Luper, Daisy Bates, oh boy, what's my girl's name? Oh, I'm trying to, Ella Baker.

443
00:53:57,000 --> 00:54:08,000
Those ladies took us aside and told us we were okay. You know, they had their problems with some of the leadership at the time too.

444
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:18,000
And, you know, I guess it was in one sense, second class citizenship for women that was still being overcome in terms of the old hierarchy.

445
00:54:18,000 --> 00:54:31,000
And, and a leaders group, you know, organizations did this, which was one of the things that put me outside of a lot of it and I think made me go to where I am now.

446
00:54:31,000 --> 00:54:41,000
But Reverend Rev. T.J. Jemison was one of the people that I admired because he was a country preacher.

447
00:54:41,000 --> 00:54:55,000
Reverend Walker, on the other hand, was a well-educated preacher. They were both AME ministers, but they were committed and they kept us on track.

448
00:54:55,000 --> 00:55:03,000
You know, because of them, I met Medgar Evers. I was at a meeting with him and his brother Charles, who I love.

449
00:55:03,000 --> 00:55:16,000
Charles was one of my heroes because Charles Evers, you know, Charles Evers said, you ever hit me all you lose is the swing.

450
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:26,000
He said, you're going to get the blowback. And, you know, I was philosophically, I was with him on that.

451
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:41,000
But we had a meeting at the church on South Boulevard in Baton Rouge. And I didn't realize, you know, that little, the impact of that because three days later, Medgar Evers got shot.

452
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:53,000
And I was, well, I was very upset. But I had gone, I was already back in school. I was writing for the school newspaper, cartooning for it and stuff like that.

453
00:55:53,000 --> 00:56:02,000
And staying sort of in front of the dean of students is desk almost every week for something that I had done.

454
00:56:02,000 --> 00:56:10,000
And he later told me he missed me because he enjoyed I low-confering. He was always wondering what I was going to do next.

455
00:56:10,000 --> 00:56:18,000
Or what we were going to do next as a staff because we had a group of, at that time, energized students.

456
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:30,000
You know, we had a reason that in 1963, 64 or 65, we had reason to want to, our president.

457
00:56:30,000 --> 00:56:49,000
Yeah. I ended up going back to school, back to Southern. I started, in fact, I went back that fall. I almost, they tried to get me for a violation of a federal injunction in the fall of 1962 because I took some kids to a few-quail elementary school.

458
00:56:49,000 --> 00:57:09,000
And I embarrassed the principal who, you know, who still didn't give a rant about us, a sort of communist outside agitators coming in and doing this and that and I explained to him in front of the TV camera that I grown up down the street from that school.

459
00:57:09,000 --> 00:57:26,000
So I wasn't exactly an outside agitator. I was an inside agitator. And I wasn't going to stop agitating. Well, they wanted to put me in jail for a violation of a federal injunction, 10 years, 10,000 out of fines that I, that I, that I,

460
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:36,000
Revin Jokes called in AA office and I think it was Gloster Current who was from Dallas.

461
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:53,000
Was the attorney that came down and talked to the district attorney in Baton Rouge, Sargent Pitcher, whom as funny as it might sound, it handled my mother's divorce and whom as a poor little kid, my grandmother,

462
00:57:53,000 --> 00:58:15,000
or their fed once or twice when he was growing up and he remembered her. But my grandmother was very well known around Baton Rouge, you know, because of her, her church work and her choirs and this and that and the fact that she was, so all of those factors I think had something to do with my not going to jail because it was trumped up anyhow.

463
00:58:15,000 --> 00:58:27,000
And the first thing was they were trying the injunction was against core. I was a car carry and a NAACP member at times. So NAA was not enjoying in that sense.

464
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:41,000
And NAACP also had the, had the litigatory for us. They had, you know, they, they had, they're a good marshal and people like that. And so, you know, the, they, they weren't going to win that fight.

465
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:54,000
And as I said, when we went to jail earlier in 61 that the charges that they tried to put us to lay on us then were kicked out before we ever got to court.

466
00:58:54,000 --> 00:59:16,000
Because of the, you know, they were basically unconstitutional. It was something that was punitive that they were trying to do to make a shut up. They didn't do that instead. Some of us went in different directions. You know, I used to send nasty cartoons to the, to the Klan rally, Klan rally. I knew it didn't know who I was.

467
00:59:16,000 --> 00:59:30,000
I was never known who I was on the streets, but I picked on the, I picked on the clan. I still pick on, you know, they couldn't, I don't want to say just the conservatives because I think anybody who's doing wrong.

468
00:59:30,000 --> 00:59:37,000
But I'm as a registered independent. I have the right to do that. And I still do.

469
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:50,000
So we're back with Chuck Siler. We, you'll notice that we did move locations because turns out that the planet actually moves.

470
00:59:50,000 --> 01:00:00,000
So our light has shifted. So so have we, Chuck, if we could pick up, fortunately, due to time, we're going to move a little bit faster than we have been.

471
01:00:00,000 --> 01:00:18,000
Okay. We have been talking about your work with, in protesting with the NAACP. I wonder if we should move on to leaving college and going west and then your work around the North.

472
01:00:18,000 --> 01:00:38,000
I got involved with the theater. So I'm with the American theater being with Frank Silvera. It managed to trade off a production design for some acting classes and a little bit of money and things like that.

473
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:50,000
I started what was going to later become some time in Hollywood. I did work a little bit with Willis Thomas and the guys at the Hollywood NAACP in the seventies.

474
01:00:50,000 --> 01:01:04,000
But I was drafted in 67 and I wound up going through one of the those funny things careers in the military that probably would make a good sitcom.

475
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:22,000
Because I was, I had to go to Vietnam to get the job that I wanted. Oh, you know, that I would that I enjoyed doing or and it was basically because I had been through here we go, nuclear weapon school.

476
01:01:22,000 --> 01:01:39,000
Though I had a degree in art and a lot of experience of writing for newspapers and I did manage for three months to be an editor of my college newspaper just so I could legitimately say that I had done that and I had to have some,

477
01:01:39,000 --> 01:01:58,000
all some folk in that administration lobbying on my the health to do the president didn't want that. But it happened in my last summer at the school I did edit the newspaper and that next fall I edited the alumni news letters.

478
01:01:58,000 --> 01:02:08,000
So I graduated from Southern, I finished officially in January of 66 after going back to school.

479
01:02:08,000 --> 01:02:21,000
I my stay in California the first time was fairly short, not quite eight months, nine months. I went back, I came back to the States after the military.

480
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:38,000
Now in the military again, we ran into I was on charge of quarters the night that Martin Luther King was killed and being one of the I was one of the older guys in the company. I was 24 at the time.

481
01:02:38,000 --> 01:02:58,000
I was a late drafty, you know, I didn't know I was going to have to go and there was turnmoyle we had to talk folk out of I was at Fort Huachuca, Arizona at the time and we had to talk folk out of fights.

482
01:02:58,000 --> 01:03:27,000
I had to talk to some white officers who were afraid to let black soldiers go into things and I had to tell them how not to go into some of the communities in Tucson because the Hispanic and small black community that they had then they were more afraid of what might happen there than what was going to happen in the other communities where they were more likely to have problems and that was the way community.

483
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:49,000
But the managed to get through that it was not a good time. When I got to Vietnam, I wound up instead of being a truck driver as they had wanted me to do after that strange odyssey from nuclear weapons to light vehicle driver school.

484
01:03:49,000 --> 01:04:09,000
And because I could type and I already had a degree in things like that I was sent to an AG section as a senior clerk and I wound up because someone told them about that editing the AG newspaper after about three weeks of doing that.

485
01:04:09,000 --> 01:04:11,000
What did they do?

486
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:30,000
I did an AG general. The information office needed a replacement. I come in a clerk who was from California and considered me a homeboy as they used to do told the guys to say we got a guy over who's got experience as a writer.

487
01:04:30,000 --> 01:04:44,000
He had seen a scrapbook that I had with some of my stuff in it and Fred Carl who was in COIC of the office called me over and asked if I might be interested in the job.

488
01:04:44,000 --> 01:05:01,000
They knew I was an artist because I started cartooning in the AG newspaper which was a memograph sheet. I learned the draw. I learned etching from doing a memograph and dinner.

489
01:05:01,000 --> 01:05:18,000
I was like, oh, okay. Naturally I said yes. I had a chance to travel, do stories and things like that. We were attached to the first logistical command which was a command information office.

490
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:32,000
I got to play with a little radio. We wrote stuff for television. We did a variety of things. I hate to see I enjoyed that part of the military service.

491
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:45,000
We had some problems because again we ran into racism. It was deeply embedded in the older NCOs.

492
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:58,000
I met Grendel Howard who later became first female sergeant major of the Army who was a good friend of Fred Carl who was my NCOIC during that time. She came to visit.

493
01:05:58,000 --> 01:06:13,000
There was a major who later became a general Sherian Cadoria who went to Southern. She was a major at the time that I was there and was kind of surprised because she was a senior my freshman year at Southern.

494
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:31,000
Here is another Southern who showed up in the office. So head friends. General Richards used the fact that I had a top secret clearance from nuclear weapons to be able to do some sessions and things like that.

495
01:06:31,000 --> 01:06:45,000
I didn't want to be clear to do but he could activate my clearance when he needed it and did. I got to see the country. I got to write about the black soldiers who were doing things.

496
01:06:45,000 --> 01:06:57,000
I got to see the whole town news releases which were something that I guys weren't getting a lot of but then again I was the only black guy that I knew of at the time in the field doing stuff.

497
01:06:57,000 --> 01:07:13,000
There's a guy named Arnold Buschwa who was a cameraman in New Orleans, Channel 6. Arnold was on the Mo Pick team and I happened to go out with them when they were getting ready to do a story.

498
01:07:13,000 --> 01:07:29,000
We didn't realize for 30 years that we had met each other at the time until we started talking when they did that. I came back, went to work for Southern. I was hired as sports information director and assistant public context director.

499
01:07:29,000 --> 01:07:45,000
Can I interrupt in this afternoon question which is, I mean you had this position in Vietnam where you were sort of you were a voice for the black soldier or helping to sense and do things.

500
01:07:45,000 --> 01:08:05,000
I had to point to a boy that showed that one point that before I started doing it we had probably 5% of the hometown news releases.

501
01:08:05,000 --> 01:08:15,000
Not the news stories, this guy is a mechanic doing this kind of story.

502
01:08:15,000 --> 01:08:26,000
Now we were all doing stories, those were little pick up things, take a picture of a guy, write a brief little thing, send it down to Long Binh. it would go out to their hometown newspaper.

503
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:34,000
You know, who were they were from, those kind of things, what we put in so they know where to send it.

504
01:08:34,000 --> 01:08:44,000
Some of the guys that I met were talking about earlier like Charlie Black from St. Louis. These were guys that I just happened to be because I was older.

505
01:08:44,000 --> 01:08:50,000
And you know, they would come through and we'd run into each other and talk.

506
01:08:50,000 --> 01:09:00,000
And I went out to this orphanage and we were talking earlier about this.

507
01:09:00,000 --> 01:09:10,000
There were kids who had lost limbs. We saw a kid who had his job blown away.

508
01:09:10,000 --> 01:09:15,000
I mean, he didn't have the lower half of his face and they had to figure out ways to feed him this and that.

509
01:09:15,000 --> 01:09:19,000
I didn't think he was going to survive.

510
01:09:19,000 --> 01:09:30,000
But the things that you saw every day were, you know, the things that you see in a war, even if you're not a grunt, you know, if you're not an infantryman,

511
01:09:30,000 --> 01:09:38,000
are things that you can't often talk to people about when you get back because they have no way of understanding it.

512
01:09:38,000 --> 01:09:50,000
I had some good friends who were guys who were LAPD. In fact, when I, in the 70s, who had been over there, we could have conversations, we could talk about what we had seen.

513
01:09:50,000 --> 01:09:57,000
And they understood the fact that there were race rides in Vietnam. People don't talk about that.

514
01:09:57,000 --> 01:10:05,000
Okay. There were times when troops were coming in from the fields and trying to tell guys who were stationed in or near cities.

515
01:10:05,000 --> 01:10:12,000
My information office was at Heddon, here, or at his compound in Qui Nhơn.

516
01:10:12,000 --> 01:10:20,000
There were fights downtown between soldiers who were coming in out of the field, black and white soldiers because white soldiers would tell black guys, you can't come in here.

517
01:10:20,000 --> 01:10:32,000
They were waiting to make it hold up. You know, we all green, supposedly. You know, and it doesn't mean light green, go over here, dark green, go over there.

518
01:10:32,000 --> 01:10:37,000
Or that wasn't the way, you know, it was supposed to work.

519
01:10:37,000 --> 01:10:44,000
I tended to be an advocate at times with it necessary when guys were getting in trouble.

520
01:10:44,000 --> 01:10:54,000
I was doing a little troop pushing when I was at Fort Wat Chuka. And I found out that a lot of guys, I had a platoon of guys at one point that I was in charge of.

521
01:10:54,000 --> 01:11:06,000
That had all been for the most probably 70% of them have been in the stockade. Usually for things that had nothing to do with crime.

522
01:11:06,000 --> 01:11:18,000
But I was a Hispanic guy because they didn't understand the language. So in my platoon I started getting the guys who spoke English to work with the guys who didn't.

523
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:23,000
You know, to help them because they were going to need that kind of thing.

524
01:11:23,000 --> 01:11:28,000
When I came out of the military, I still haven't changed, like I said, basically.

525
01:11:28,000 --> 01:11:37,000
With what I do as a cartoonist now, it's a running commentary on what's going on. And yes, I pick up and point out racism.

526
01:11:37,000 --> 01:11:48,000
You know, and it comes from both sides. Like I said, I'm an independent. I see some things from the Democrats and I see it from the Republicans.

527
01:11:48,000 --> 01:11:59,000
My best friend used to be a media guy for the Libertarian Party. One of my oldest clothes, but we fussed and fight.

528
01:11:59,000 --> 01:12:11,000
We were probably doing until we were 90 if we could live that long. But I was able to going back and I have to go back in 1962 for a minute.

529
01:12:11,000 --> 01:12:16,000
Two of the guys who we came, good friends of mine, Bill Rusky and Larry Wigg at the time.

530
01:12:16,000 --> 01:12:23,000
We're two young white guys who were trying to write a book about the civil rights movement. I don't know whatever happened after a while.

531
01:12:23,000 --> 01:12:29,000
But Lawrence Maxson Wigg was a part of the Maxson family that the truck people in.

532
01:12:29,000 --> 01:12:35,000
They talked me out and going to a Klan rally. They left me actually.

533
01:12:36,000 --> 01:12:43,000
I wanted to go to a Klan rally with them and hide in the trunk of their car at Stone Mountain. That's how silly I was.

534
01:12:43,000 --> 01:12:59,000
But they were an LSU for the summer and did that. What I learned was, you know, I think during that period of time was how to take people according to who they were and how they were to me as opposed to.

535
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:11,000
Because I made some friends that I couldn't ask somebody just because they were black to risk their life for me.

536
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:22,000
And some guys did some things that were about the fact that we were friends as opposed to the fact that we had different colors.

537
01:13:22,000 --> 01:13:30,000
I try to look at the heart of the person. I think that's what's important to me in terms of where I am now.

538
01:13:30,000 --> 01:13:38,000
And again, Sam Caster was my buddy in Baton Rouge. You died back in the wet 99, 2000.

539
01:13:38,000 --> 01:13:47,000
But Sam was the one who said, you know, to him, you know, the full race of the men were A, A, B, B, and O.

540
01:13:47,000 --> 01:13:59,000
And again, you can't tell who's what because we laughed. We were both Bs, and both our wives were old. So we said, well, we're in the racial marriages, even though they looked the same.

541
01:13:59,000 --> 01:14:10,000
But if I'm going to the hospital, he says, I'm not going to ask you for a piece of, I'm not going to say give me some skin. He says, but I will say give me some blood.

542
01:14:10,000 --> 01:14:19,000
And so we started looking at it and then why we were friends because sometimes friends have to question why your friends.

543
01:14:19,000 --> 01:14:27,000
I learned over the years when I worked in Southern, I'm trying to catch up so we can move forward.

544
01:14:27,000 --> 01:14:39,000
Some of the guys that I had a good chance to work with when they were students, Mel Blount, Mel Blount + Harold Carmichael + (likely) Isiah Robinson, if you're a football fan, I see a Robinson who played for the Rams.

545
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:48,000
I was a few years older than them. I was 26, most of these guys are 21, 22. And I still say refer to them as my kids, okay?

546
01:14:48,000 --> 01:14:56,000
Because I was just older enough to deal with the Bob Love and I who played for the Bulls or classmates.

547
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:05,000
And we were, you know, well, he was a year behind me, but we were good for you know, the friendships that you develop over these times and doing different things.

548
01:15:05,000 --> 01:15:16,000
When I worked at Grambling, or well, not at Glaming, but for Black Associated Sports Enterprise, this was the first Black Sports Network on television.

549
01:15:16,000 --> 01:15:25,000
It should have been, it should have been what became BET.

550
01:15:26,000 --> 01:15:34,000
But we were trying to do things. I was trying to convince people that we should do films on folk like Robert Smalls.

551
01:15:34,000 --> 01:15:51,000
And they were going, who's Robert Smalls? Well, I had a bad attitude in those days and I called a couple of producers some things that they didn't really like when it came down to being saying you're stupid, but I didn't have to, I didn't have that restraint, you know.

552
01:15:52,000 --> 01:16:01,000
After I ran my own business at Freelance, as a writer, as an artist, I did little film work here, little TV work there.

553
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:05,000
I did some ghost writing, rewriting scripts for other people and things like that.

554
01:16:05,000 --> 01:16:09,000
Some freelance public relations for about 10 years.

555
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:18,000
Moved back to Louisiana and went to work for the first division of Black culture of any state in the country.

556
01:16:18,000 --> 01:16:29,000
Our friend Ruth Wesley was director Edwin Edwards, the guy they called Edwin Edwards Louisiana, started that.

557
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:34,000
Edwin Edwards did more for Black people than most of the other people who followed him.

558
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:42,000
And for some strange reason, though they never mentioned this, Edwin Edwards always left the state in black.

559
01:16:42,000 --> 01:16:46,000
Budget wise, the state was always in the black when Edwin Edwards was running it.

560
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:54,000
Now, like him or not, and I have friends who hate him, I try to look down the middle at it.

561
01:16:55,000 --> 01:17:02,000
Why do you hate the guy who was supposedly Edwin Edwards who made money for everybody and who only took a dollar a year for his job?

562
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:06,000
Yeah, okay. So maybe you should have paid him a percentage of what he made.

563
01:17:06,000 --> 01:17:15,000
You know, logically, for me, that might have made more sense because if he was going to see the state and he was making money, it made, you know.

564
01:17:15,000 --> 01:17:23,000
But we made strides then, I think, because we were able to move agenda forward.

565
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:34,000
You know, we put out, I put out a national thing to all of the Black radio stations in the country or the radio stations with majority black audiences about.

566
01:17:34,000 --> 01:17:38,000
And I'm not taking credit for this, but it became a thing.

567
01:17:38,000 --> 01:17:45,000
Black 365, Black was the idea, you know, we're not just Black and February.

568
01:17:45,000 --> 01:17:50,000
Okay. By that time, we are Black 365 days a year.

569
01:17:50,000 --> 01:17:54,000
Let's go with this. The Mayor of Baton Rouge could tell you about that.

570
01:17:54,000 --> 01:18:04,000
Keep hold of it because he was on radio at the time and I used to do a few things with him to let him know, you know, to put history into his show.

571
01:18:04,000 --> 01:18:09,000
He was concerned about that. He was good. He went back to law school, became a legislator.

572
01:18:09,000 --> 01:18:15,000
And now he's on his second or third term as Mayor of Baton Rouge.

573
01:18:15,000 --> 01:18:16,000
The...

574
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:22,000
Can you come in on culture and politics being intertwined and not separate entities?

575
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:26,000
They are very much so because politics impact culture.

576
01:18:26,000 --> 01:18:37,000
And a part of how that happens is if you are not concerned about the culture and you are in power, you can hurt cultures by overlooking them.

577
01:18:37,000 --> 01:18:54,000
You know, I'm going to a meeting next week in Carrolton, where one of the former City Council members is trying to create a project that stresses the diversity of the city, which is minority white technically.

578
01:18:54,000 --> 01:19:03,000
But it's in terms of the majority of the City Council and those who govern it white.

579
01:19:03,000 --> 01:19:09,000
Our conservative also.

580
01:19:09,000 --> 01:19:13,000
So we have to deal with that, but it's how you have to deal with that.

581
01:19:13,000 --> 01:19:22,000
Okay. Going back again, I moved back to Louisiana after I left the original Black culture, I went to work for this Louisiana State Museum.

582
01:19:22,000 --> 01:19:25,000
It took about not quite a year off.

583
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:30,000
But when I went to the Louisiana State Museum, I was the second Black curator there.

584
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:38,000
I was the first Black Louisianan and first male to have a curatorial job there.

585
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:46,000
We did get involved and my wife knows I'm not going to stay on this, but I fell in love with the Mardi Gras Indians.

586
01:19:47,000 --> 01:20:01,000
And I did that in part because of the fact that I heard about my Indian heritage in the family and this and that from my father, from my uncle and from, you know, bits and pieces of this and that I wanted to find out about it.

587
01:20:01,000 --> 01:20:04,000
So in 94 I did an exhibit on that.

588
01:20:04,000 --> 01:20:18,000
One of the funny things about it was a white photographer decided that I was being prejudice because I, the show was about African-American photographers looking at the Black Indians and the Indians.

589
01:20:18,000 --> 01:20:24,000
And I want to have a day asking to bring a note from his mother, certified that he was Black.

590
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:28,000
And, you know, he left us alone after that.

591
01:20:28,000 --> 01:20:33,000
But we've never been great friends since then who won't be probably.

592
01:20:33,000 --> 01:20:36,000
But, you know, I'm not going to miss him. I have enough friends.

593
01:20:36,000 --> 01:20:42,000
The thing that I discovered along the way was a game.

594
01:20:42,000 --> 01:20:48,000
Inter-office politics also, not just, you know, state, local government.

595
01:20:48,000 --> 01:21:01,000
But it filters all the way down to the basic level where you have to sometimes remind people that look, stop and think before you react.

596
01:21:01,000 --> 01:21:16,000
Because I looked at it like this. I said the first thing the average white person that I know and I'm using that generically is going to think about is how to do the white thing.

597
01:21:16,000 --> 01:21:22,000
The people who want to do right will think that would stop.

598
01:21:22,000 --> 01:21:27,000
You know, I'm not, I try not to be Black reactive.

599
01:21:27,000 --> 01:21:35,000
You know, I'm not going to just react out of what I, I've accepted what I am culturally.

600
01:21:35,000 --> 01:21:41,000
I know who I am. I define me, you know, I come myself an American African.

601
01:21:41,000 --> 01:21:54,000
I'm an African descent. But everybody on this planet according to the folk that I know think about it, you know, and who are not bound by some religious myth or whatever.

602
01:21:54,000 --> 01:22:00,000
Or understand where mankind started in that place we now call Africa.

603
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:08,000
So, we're all Africans in that sense. Maybe as Johnson clear the poet said, we should call this planet Africa.

604
01:22:08,000 --> 01:22:15,000
And get on with it, you know, because the climate made us look different.

605
01:22:15,000 --> 01:22:26,000
And how we played with history comes out of who became the powers who got to write the story, you know, that line again.

606
01:22:26,000 --> 01:22:36,000
You know, when I found that, until the lion writes his own story, the tale of the hunt will always glorify the hunter.

607
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:41,000
I, a friend, Kalid Hafiz, that I worked with at Jazz Fest in New Orleans.

608
01:22:41,000 --> 01:22:50,000
I used to represent the museum doing things on a Black heritage stage. Then it became the African heritage stage, you know, over a period of time.

609
01:22:50,000 --> 01:23:03,000
We, you have to, we had to make gradual changes to get people to understand what the culture was about and how we were approaching it so that it could be informative for everyone.

610
01:23:03,000 --> 01:23:10,000
And hopefully elevate the level of consciousness for all of the people we were dealing with.

611
01:23:10,000 --> 01:23:18,000
How we were able to, you know, I was able to go into schools and talk to kids and tell them about what it was like being in jail because I've been in jail.

612
01:23:18,000 --> 01:23:23,000
They listened to that and understood that I wasn't kidding them.

613
01:23:23,000 --> 01:23:30,000
There's no BS here. There is, I wasn't a hero. I was a foot soldier.

614
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:38,000
I think of myself as when it comes to civil rights. I was another person who was there. I was able to make some differences.

615
01:23:38,000 --> 01:23:44,000
But my differences were on the one to one level more so than on the one to a thousand.

616
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:57,000
But I've always felt like this. I've had a little success in teaching kids about art and about history. And when I teach art, I teach art and history and music.

617
01:23:57,000 --> 01:24:04,000
So we talk about the blues, we talk about jazz, we talk about the history of African people in the world.

618
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:11,000
And the interactions between the groups of people. Why and how people think of different things?

619
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:17,000
This is what I think we need to know. I think we have to be self-defining.

620
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:28,000
I define Chuck Siler based on what I learned from history. But I've had a chance over the years to meet all kinds of folk.

621
01:24:28,000 --> 01:24:36,000
I've had friends who did all sorts of things. You know, Lenny Bruce's mother brought me chicken soup when I had the flu.

622
01:24:36,000 --> 01:24:43,000
Sally Marr was a thing. And I knew how to do other friends who were comics.

623
01:24:43,000 --> 01:24:50,000
They knew me because I was a cartoonist and I was accepted as a comic because I did cartoons.

624
01:24:50,000 --> 01:24:57,000
And sometimes wrote a line here or two. I've been an official cartoonist for two comedy clubs.

625
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:02,000
The comedy story at one point in the early 70s and the improv in the early 80s.

626
01:25:02,000 --> 01:25:10,000
Because I lived in the neighborhood. I hung out there. The comics knew I was a writer. They knew I was a cartoonist.

627
01:25:10,000 --> 01:25:22,000
We had sometimes very serious discussions about perceptions. How we perceived each other. What was funny? Why was it funny?

628
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:31,000
If you could tell a black joke, I could tell a good Polish joke. I could tell a joke about anybody if it were that way.

629
01:25:31,000 --> 01:25:38,000
And I wasn't afraid to because if you thought you could bring it, if you can't take it, don't bring it.

630
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:48,000
It was the case. And you know, I've got some old friends that we can't laugh out loud about some of the things that we've laughed about over the years.

631
01:25:48,000 --> 01:25:55,000
But they all understand that the bottom line is the humanity.

632
01:25:55,000 --> 01:26:04,000
This is what we have to work to work. And this is how we have to deal with those people who are too stupid to understand.

633
01:26:04,000 --> 01:26:12,000
You know, who one plus one has to be three. You're giving time now.

634
01:26:12,000 --> 01:26:21,000
I was going to say, I think that might be perfect right there. I was going to ask you a final question if you could comment on the power of the pen and the power of humor.

635
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:31,000
I think this. People, you know, I have a good audience. You know, we were talking earlier that was still you.

636
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:40,000
I'm regular, I'm editorial page. Can I tune this for the Louisiana weekly? The black commentator uses my stuff.

637
01:26:40,000 --> 01:26:48,000
I've got, oh God, 10 people, good friends, the Louisiana folk and that puts it out. Whatever I send it to them.

638
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:58,000
I've written about it and I still do right occasionally about it. You know, do a little review, things like that.

639
01:26:58,000 --> 01:27:07,000
I've got friends, I guess, with every walk of life. A lot of them are in academia. Some of them are now retired from there.

640
01:27:07,000 --> 01:27:16,000
A lot of them are professional journalists. You know, I hear from them when if I get slightly off-track, you know,

641
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:23,000
if I don't use enough female characters in the cartoons, I have some lady friends who will say, you don't use enough women.

642
01:27:23,000 --> 01:27:33,000
I said, okay, you know, I'm, I'm, let me remind me if I, you know, because you do what's, what's instinctive, what's natural.

643
01:27:33,000 --> 01:27:42,000
I find that if I can make a person laugh more often than not, they'll remember what I said.

644
01:27:43,000 --> 01:27:53,000
If I hear, I notice that when sometimes I do things and I get responses from places that I didn't expect or from people that I didn't expect to hear from.

645
01:27:53,000 --> 01:28:07,000
Okay, I had a instructor who died a few weeks ago. Name was Huel Perkins. When we did the Baton Rouge bus boycott piece, I was talking about Doug Brinkley and some of the other guys who were there dugin.

646
01:28:07,000 --> 01:28:12,000
Like I said, we were on different ends of the podium, but we caught everybody in the middle of the dead.

647
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:27,000
I told the story about how Dr. Perkins used to close his classes. I had a humanity class under him in an amphitheater style role, a choir role, and I will always set up at the back where I could watch everything going on.

648
01:28:27,000 --> 01:28:37,000
Dr. Perkins used to like to close with Ross Dyer with Cyrano de Bergerac, who my later found out was the father of modern science fiction in real life.

649
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:56,000
Yeah. He would cite rock sounds, realization that Cyrano was the person who wrote those letters, of Christian.

650
01:28:56,000 --> 01:29:08,000
And girls would get up and walk out of the class, leave their purses, leave their coats in the wintertime, and come back in embarrassed.

651
01:29:08,000 --> 01:29:21,000
And I sit back and say, I got to be like that. You know, I said, I want to be like him. I want to be able to do that. I want to be able to make them listen.

652
01:29:21,000 --> 01:29:33,000
You know, he was one of the teachers that I had who could convince a class like that. You know, the charismatic teacher.

653
01:29:33,000 --> 01:29:43,000
So you try to take a little bit of each one of those, but I had him almost fall out of his seat because we used to play tennis together.

654
01:29:43,000 --> 01:30:00,000
And I tell him he was the most literate trash talker tennis player that I met in my house. And he loved it. But when I wrote my last column from a student newspaper, he sent me a note telling me to keep on doing that.

655
01:30:00,000 --> 01:30:20,000
And he says, you honor. He encouraged me. Go on with that. So, you know, here I am 50 some of our years later, trying to do the same thing. And when I look back at the people who contributed to who I am, I carry a little piece of all of them.

656
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:35,000
You know, when John Hope Franklin and Lonnie Bunch and the guy sent the letter saying, you know, they want you to do this. It was just about, I got that letter about a few days after Ethan was born.

657
01:30:35,000 --> 01:30:55,000
Okay, I said, I got a grandson. I got to leave something so that one day when my son takes his son to that museum, if they want to call up the interview and see it, I want him to understand, you know, something about his heritage, his personal heritage.

658
01:30:55,000 --> 01:31:06,000
You know, who raised your daddy? You know, so you can go out there and you can be your own man because that's what it's about.

659
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:17,000
You know, it's the same thing that you get when you, when I talk to kids at my workshops, you know, we sit down and we talk about music.

660
01:31:17,000 --> 01:31:31,000
I tell them about who Alvin Batiste was, who Danny Barker was, who these musicians that came out of our whole town, the Marsalises, you know, who Henry Butler is.

661
01:31:31,000 --> 01:31:40,000
I let them hear the music, let them hear brass band music, talk to them about the art of what the Mardi Gras Indians do, mobile art.

662
01:31:40,000 --> 01:31:51,000
Okay, every time, you know, you come into a museum like this, one of the greatest collections of folk art that you're going to find is right here where we sit.

663
01:31:51,000 --> 01:32:03,000
Okay, Harry Robinson has been collecting for years. The fact that we have to celebrate this, we have to understand why it's done.

664
01:32:03,000 --> 01:32:11,000
What motivates the artist is not money because if it were just money, I'd like to be wealthy.

665
01:32:11,000 --> 01:32:21,000
But I don't stop doing the art because of the fact that I'm not wealthy. Okay, I have something to say and I have an audience. I play with that.

666
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:35,000
You know, I try to reach the audience. My audience extends it. And sometimes I hear from places like I said that I never expected to hear from because a friend of mine sent it out to his business list.

667
01:32:35,000 --> 01:32:49,000
And I have one guy in California who does that. He's got a big list. I wish mine were. But here's people who rescinded, you know, email. If I had email 30 years, if we had email in 1960,

668
01:32:49,000 --> 01:32:58,000
the Civil Rights Movement would have been over by that day, 365. The way we were approaching it because we would have been hitting people.

669
01:32:58,000 --> 01:33:06,000
You would have been able to open your computer without getting us. You know, the thing is that when I look back at that, I said,

670
01:33:06,000 --> 01:33:19,000
boy, when I had meld in those guys at Southern playing ball, I said, if I had emailed that, you know, it was memio graph copy walk in, go to a press conference.

671
01:33:19,000 --> 01:33:34,000
And if you had to do it with the pro teams, and I had that once with the Rams, I literally memorized my stats. So I wouldn't have to stand up there and constantly refer to it because of what was expected.

672
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:42,000
And here's this guy from this little black school. Okay. So those teachers who told me you had to be three times as good.

673
01:33:42,000 --> 01:34:00,000
We're bringing my air saying, you know, you got to be sure how good you are. And it's something that I think was a part of that motivation. And it's a part of what is ongoing in terms of wouldn't motivate me to try to continuously make a statement.

674
01:34:00,000 --> 01:34:11,000
You know, and to make a statement that is a human statement more so than just a stupid, you know, someone asked me once Mr. Hubbard gene Paul, I studied with gene Paul Hubbard and Frank Hayden.

675
01:34:11,000 --> 01:34:14,000
Frank Hayden was a sculptor.

676
01:34:14,000 --> 01:34:27,000
We had a lot of one on one conversations Harold Cureau, who taught me things that paid my rent for a long time. He taught commercial art and graphic design and that.

677
01:34:27,000 --> 01:34:43,000
These guys always stressed the fact that we had to, you know, be able to get out and not be them. You know, it's don't say you're not a little gene Paul Hubbard.

678
01:34:43,000 --> 01:34:51,000
You're not a little Frank Hayden. You're going to be we sending you out to be Chuck Siler.

679
01:34:51,000 --> 01:35:13,000
And this is what you, you know, this is what I represent. You know, all of those people who, I named the guys who were to jail with me, the Willie Bradford, Willie Bradford jerked me away from a door that would have taken off my left hand because a deputy sheriff slapped on it.

680
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:23,000
There was a lady I forgot to mention and I got to do this to close it if before in 1962 when I was doing the broader registration project.

681
01:35:23,000 --> 01:35:38,000
There was a lady who lived in an area that they called the park. I remember her name is Miss Williams. I could be wrong after all this time, but she reminded me when she went to register the vote. She got front twice.

682
01:35:38,000 --> 01:35:53,000
Okay, over BS. But she was determined. She was 84 years old in 1962 that she was going to vote before she died.

683
01:35:53,000 --> 01:36:02,000
She was going to be a registered voter. She was going to have the card. And the third time she went in, I went with her.

684
01:36:02,000 --> 01:36:16,000
Now, I was young and stupid and not unlike a lot of folk. I was 19 years old. I had my gun stashed under my jacket in the back.

685
01:36:16,000 --> 01:36:29,000
And if anybody had done anything, it could have been a real bad scene that day. And I would have been remembered for something else. Okay, but she was going to go in there.

686
01:36:29,000 --> 01:36:41,000
When she walked through, it was like, lowly sea lion walking through those same guys about seven or eight months before when we got out of jail at January.

687
01:36:41,000 --> 01:37:00,000
For whatever reason, they wanted to intimidate one old lady. And they failed horribly. Because she walked through. She reminded me of Mary McLeod Bethune, but doing I always think of her when I remember this lady dressed well, put on a nice suit.

688
01:37:00,000 --> 01:37:14,000
And Charles were going. And someone drove us down. I forget who it was. But we walked in. And like I said, I was prepared to shoot somebody.

689
01:37:14,000 --> 01:37:26,000
If they had decided to go that far, they didn't because when she walked in, she was in charge. They moved aside. She walked.

690
01:37:26,000 --> 01:37:44,000
And she walked into the register. I was, I was sure you can't go in there. I said, no problem. I stood back against the wall. You know, and I got a corner. Okay, vantage point, advantage point as readers always look for. Okay.

691
01:37:44,000 --> 01:37:59,000
And I was waiting. And I was standing there like this. And I was pressing that little burr at her. Because I wanted to say when she came out, she had to smile on her face. Okay.

692
01:38:00,000 --> 01:38:21,000
That made all of it worth it. It was, you know, as good as it could get at that moment because she got what she wanted. And she got the vote before she died.

693
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:41,000
And, you know, you think about being 84 in 1962. Her parents had been slaves. Okay, to her, it was important. You know, I'm, I'm a person who gets upset when somebody tells me they can't go. They're not going to vote.

694
01:38:41,000 --> 01:38:51,000
I don't care if you, you know, vote for the person who's going to do you the least harm if nothing else.

695
01:38:51,000 --> 01:39:04,000
But try to understand what and why you're doing it. You know, understand. I'm, I learned from my wife every day. My wife being a government teacher.

696
01:39:04,000 --> 01:39:13,000
You know, I want of her better students. And what happens? I passed the test when I can make her laugh.

697
01:39:13,000 --> 01:39:32,000
Because to a large degree, that's what it's about. If I can put an idea that she passes on to me out and get a reaction from my public, one of the things that artists always want. And I think it's, it happens in anything else.

698
01:39:32,000 --> 01:39:48,000
You don't want on week. You want a positive reaction or negatively, you want a reaction. I don't care what the reaction is because I got a good friend who's a Republican who is die hard.

699
01:39:48,000 --> 01:40:03,000
Okay, die hard, black Republican. He's not quite as far right as out of west of those people. And I managed to bring him back a bit. But we have had some great arguments. But we love each other like brothers.

700
01:40:03,000 --> 01:40:21,000
And we will fight intellectually like brothers. And my point is we have less, I have less. I learned from him because I learned what that side is thinking.

701
01:40:21,000 --> 01:40:41,000
My buddy who's a libertarian. I learned what the libertarians are thinking. I have two good friends who are imams. Okay. They aren't radicals. You know, they aren't going to go out and blow anybody up. They are parents.

702
01:40:41,000 --> 01:41:05,000
But we can talk because my Baptist minister buddies, I haven't been, you know, I go to church for filenals. Okay. I have my own belief. It took years. And it took black preachers who didn't want to become a part of it to make me go to look.

703
01:41:05,000 --> 01:41:27,000
You know, the minister at the church that I used to attend wouldn't let me do workshops for the registration in his church because he was afraid. Okay. I was not being afraid. And I couldn't respect him because of the fact that how are you going to tell me you believe in something that you scared to stand up for it.

704
01:41:27,000 --> 01:41:54,000
You know, I said, what would Jesus Christ do to you? You know, what would you have to say about you if you didn't, you know, what would the prophet Muhammad have to say if you didn't stand up? You know, I liked the Quakers because the American friends service committee helped us out a lot during the civil rights movement. Yeah, we had, they gave us places to meet. We did what we could, you know.

705
01:41:54,000 --> 01:42:05,000
So that's, you know, I don't know if there's much more to say. I would be, I would be the same. Stop.

706
01:42:05,000 --> 01:42:12,000
I didn't want to stop. I don't want to stop. But we got to get on our planet. Of course, but so let me just say, again, thank you so much.

707
01:42:12,000 --> 01:42:22,000
Oh, hey, I appreciate this has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
